id not enter''\n|-\n| {{flagicon|CRC}} [[CCCF Championship|1953]]||Fifth place||6||2||1||3||10||13\n|- style=\"background:LemonChiffon;\"\n| {{flagicon|HON}} [[1955 CCCF Championship|1955]]||Fourth place||6||3||0||3||8||13\n|-\n| {{flagicon|ANT}} [[CCCF Championship|1957]]||colspan=7|''Did not enter''\n|-\n| {{flagicon|CUB}} [[1960 CCCF Championship|1960]]||colspan=7|''Withdrew''\n|- style=\"background:silver;\"\n| {{flagicon|CRC}} [[1961 CCCF Championship|1961]]||Runners-up||6||4||1||1||18||7\n|-\n!Total!!7/10!!41!!20!!5!!16!!100!!80\n|}\n:''*Denotes draws include knockout matches decided on [[penalty shootout (football)|penalty kicks]].''\n:''**Red border color indicates tournament was held on home soil.''\n<small> Source:<ref name=\"otros\"/> </small>\n\n;Olympic Games \nThe El Salvador national football team have competed in the Olympics on one occasion; the [[Football at the 1968 Summer Olympics|1968 games.]] They reached the first round of the competition.\n* [[Football at the 1900 Summer Olympics|1900]] to [[Football at the 1964 Summer Olympics|1964]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''Did not enter''\n* {{flagicon|MEX}} [[Football at the 1968 Summer Olympics|1968]]&nbsp;\u2013 Round 1\n* [[Football at the 1972 Summer Olympics|1972]] to [[Football at the 2016 Summer Olympics|2016]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''Did not qualify''\n<small> Source:<ref name=\"olimpicos\"/> </small>\n\n;Pan American Games \n* [[Football at the 1951 Pan American Games|1951]] to [[Football at the 1971 Pan American Games|1971]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''Did not enter''\n* {{flagicon|MEX}} [[Football at the 1975 Pan American Games|1975]]&nbsp;\u2013 Round 1\n* [[Football at the 1979 Pan American Games|1979]] to [[Football at the 1983 Pan American Games|1983]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''Did not enter''\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Football at the 1987 Pan American Games|1987]]&nbsp;\u2013 Round 1\n* [[Football at the 1991 Pan American Games|1991]] to [[Football at the 2015 Pan American Games&nbsp;\u2013 Men's tournament|2015]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''Did not enter''\n\n;Central American Games \n* {{flagicon|GUA}} [[Football at the 1973 Central American Games|1973]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[File:Bronze medal centralamerica.svg|Bronze|20px]] '''Bronze Medal'''\n* {{flagicon|SLV}} [[Football at the 1977 Central American Games|1977]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[File:Gold medal centralamerica.svg|Gold|20px]] '''Gold Medal'''\n* {{flagicon|GUA}} [[Football at the 1986 Central American Games|1986]]&nbsp;\u2013 Fourth place\n* {{flagicon|HON}} [[Football at the 1990 Central American Games|1990]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''Did not participate''\n* {{flagicon|SLV}} [[Football at the 1994 Central American Games|1994]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[File:Silver medal centralamerica.svg|Silver|20px]] '''Silver Medal'''\n* {{flagicon|PAN}} [[Football at the 1997 Central American Games|1997]]&nbsp;\u2013 Fourth place\n* {{flagicon|GUA}} [[Football at the 2001 Central American Games|2001]]&nbsp;\u2013 Round 1\n* {{flagicon|CRC}} [[Football at the 2013 Central American Games|2013]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[File:Bronze medal centralamerica.svg|Bronze|20px]] '''Bronze Medal'''\n* {{flagicon|NCA}} [[Football at the 2017 Central American Games|2017]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[File:Bronze medal centralamerica.svg|Bronze|20px]] '''Bronze Medal'''\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==Stadium==\n{{main|Estadio Jorge \"M\u00e1gico\" Gonz\u00e1lez|Estadio Cuscatl\u00e1n}}\n[[File:Estadio cuscatlan.jpg|260px|thumb|Aerial view of the [[Estadio Cuscatl\u00e1n]], El Salvador's national stadium]]\n\nEl Salvador's current [[national stadium]] is the [[Estadio Cuscatl\u00e1n]] which saw its first game in 1976. Before the opening of the Estadio Cuscatl\u00e1n the national stadium was the [[Estadio Jorge \"M\u00e1gico\" Gonz\u00e1lez|Estadio Nacional de la Flor Blanca]] (now known as Estadio Jorge \"M\u00e1gico\" Gonz\u00e1lez).\n\nDuring El Salvador's early run of existence, the team's national stadium was the Campo Marte, a 16 acre of land that housed a ministadium, (now known as ''Parque Infantil'') between 1928 and 1934.<ref name=\"Campo Marte\">{{cite web | author=Guevara, Ricardo |title= El campo para los ni\u00f1os | url=http://www.elsalvador.com/noticias/EDICIONESANTERIORES/octubre11/VIDA/ | publisher=elsalvador.com | accessdate=22 May 2011 | date=11 October 1999 |language=Spanish |trans-title=The field for the children}}</ref> Succeeding, El Salvador played at the [[Estadio Jorge \"M\u00e1gico\" Gonz\u00e1lez|Estadio Nacional de la Flor Blanca]] (now known as Estadio Jorge \"M\u00e1gico\" Gonz\u00e1lez) in [[San Salvador]], El Salvador. It was first built on 19 April 1932 during the presidency of Maximiliano Hern\u00e1ndez Mart\u00ednez in preparation for the [[1935 Central American and Caribbean Games]]. On 24 March 1935 El Salvador played its first game at the Flor Blanca against Cuba and won 4\u20131.<ref name=\"Estadio Magico\">{{cite web | author=Gomez, Omar |title= Estadio Jorge Magico Gonzalez | url=http://www.elbaloncuscatleco.com/estadiomagico.html | publisher=El Balon Cuscatleco | accessdate=19 May 2011 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jorge \"Magico\" Gonzalez Stadium}}</ref> El Salvador played at this stadium for the [[1970 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|1970 FIFA World Cup qualification]], and accomplished to qualify for the 1970 FIFA World Cup.<ref name=\"Estadio Magico\"/> A one-off hame was played at the stadium to commemorate a major refurbishment, it was the last time El Salvador played a game in the stadium, on 15 November 2000, against [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] in the [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|2002 FIFA World Cup qualification]] process.<ref name=\"Estadio Magico\"/>\n\nIn 1969, EDESSA (Estadios Deportivos de El Salvador Sociedad An\u00f3nima) first proposed the idea of a new national stadium.<ref name=\"EDESSA\">{{cite web |title=EDESSA primero ideas para la construcci\u00f3n del Estadio Cuscatl\u00e1n |url=http://www.1572-8.com/aa-company/deporte/estadiocuscatlan/estadio-historia.html |publisher=AA-Company |accessdate=19 May 2011 |date=7 June 2009 |language=Spanish |trans-title=EDESSA first thoughts for the construction of the Estadio Cuscatl\u00e1n |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615060912/http://www.1572-8.com/aa-company/deporte/estadiocuscatlan/estadio-historia.html |archivedate=15 June 2010 }}</ref> This came to fruition when the construction of the new national stadium, the Estadio Cuscatl\u00e1n, began on March 24, 1971, with then-president of El Salvador, [[Fidel S\u00e1nchez Hern\u00e1ndez|General Fidel S\u00e1nchez Hern\u00e1ndez]], breaking ground. There were options for the name such of that of San Salvador, Fraternidad, and Cuscatl\u00e1n but, of course, was named Cuscatl\u00e1n. After 5 years of construction, the stadium was opened and held its very first game on July 24, 1976, in a friendly match. The game saw [[Bundesliga|German Bundesliga]] champions [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]] play the El Salvador national football team, with the match ending in a 2\u20130 victory to the German side. The German squad featured [[1974 FIFA World Cup]] champions, such as [[Berti Vogts]], [[Rainer Bonhof]], [[Wolfgang Kleff]] and [[Jupp Heynckes]]. Also [[Allan Simonsen]], who eventually won the 1977 [[Ballon d'Or]] and later form part of [[FC Barcelona]]. El Salvador aligned itself with [[Tom\u00e1s Pineda]] (Mauricio \"Tarz\u00e1n\" Alvarenga), Guillermo \"Billy\" Rodr\u00edguez Bou, [[Ram\u00f3n Fagoaga]], [[Carlos Recinos|Humberto \"Imacasa\" Recinos]], Eduardo \"Conejo\" Vald\u00e9s, V\u00edctor \"Pato\" Valencia, Warner Sol\u00eds, [[F\u00e9lix Pineda|F\u00e9lix \"Garrobita\" Pineda]] (C\u00e9sar \"Piscucha\" Acevedo), [[Luis Ram\u00edrez Zapata|Luis \"Pel\u00e9\" Ram\u00edrez Zapata]] ([[Luis Abraham Coreas|Abraham Coreas]]) & [[Isma\u00e9l D\u00edaz (Salvadoran footballer)|Ismael \"Cisco\" D\u00edaz]] ([[David Arnoldo Cabrera|David Cabrera]]). While Borussia played with [[Wolfgang Kneib]], [[Hans-J\u00fcrgen Wittkamp]], [[Berti Vogts]], [[Horst Wohlers]], [[Dietmar Danner]], [[Hans Klinkhammer]], [[Carsten Nielsen]], [[Uli Stielike]], [[Jupp Heynckes]] and [[Allan Simonsen]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Zelada|first=Victor|title=La primera pincelada azul|url=http://www.elsalvador.com/mwedh/epaper/20110725/EDH20110725DEP024P.PDF|accessdate=3 November 2011|newspaper=El Diario de Hoy (El Salvador)|date=25 July 2011}}</ref>  Since that match, El Salvador has used the stadium for almost every major home game, and it is the official [[national stadium|home stadium]] of the El Salvador national football team and the Salvadoran club [[Alianza F.C. (San Salvador)|Alianza FC]].<ref name=\"Stadium\">{{cite web|title=Monumental Estadio Cuscatl\u00e1n |url=http://www.1572-8.com/aa-company/deporte/estadiocuscatlan/estadio-historia.html |publisher=elsalvadorguia.com |accessdate=2010-11-11 |date=2005-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615060912/http://www.1572-8.com/aa-company/deporte/estadiocuscatlan/estadio-historia.html |archivedate=June 15, 2010 }}</ref>  On May 25, 1978, EDESSA agreed to sign a 99-year lease of the stadium to CLIMA (Asociaci\u00f3n de Clubes de Liga Mayor A) to operate and control which events are held there.<ref name=\"History\"/>\n\nThe Estadio Cuscatl\u00e1n also features the following specifications:<ref name=\"Stadium\"/>\n\n* 45,925 capacity\n* 15 entrances\n* 10 ticket offices\n* An irrigation system and French drain\n* 4 fully equipped dressing rooms and a gymnasium\n* A large 50 m<sup>2</sup> [[LCD]] high-definition screen\n* 6 robotic cameras strategically placed at the stadium for transmission on the large screen\n* Internal sound system with [[Dolby Digital#Dolby Digital Surround EX|Dolby Digital Surround]]\n* 16 booths for radio and television transmission\n* 3 electronic lighting towers, which have their north and south towers with 22 [[Mirror|beacons]] and in the center with 24 beacons and 10 [[halogen lamps]] each\n* Parking for 8,500 cars\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Schedule and results==\nThe following is El Salvador's schedule and results for the last 12 months.\n\n{{legend2|#CCFFCC|Win|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|#FFFFCC|Draw|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|#FFCCCC|Loss|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n\n===2019===\n{{football box collapsible\n|format = 1\n|date = 2 June 2019\n|time = 19:00 [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n|round = [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]\n|score = 1\u20130\n|report = https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2019/06/02/world/friendlies/el-salvador/haiti/3023401/\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|SLV}}\n|goals1 = [[David Rugamas|Rugamas]] {{goal|76}}\n|team2 = {{fb|HAI}}\n|goals2 = \n|stadium = [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium]]\n|location = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]\n|attendance = \n|referee = Oliver Vergara ([[Panamanian Football Federation|Panama]])\n|result = W\n}}\n{{football box collapsible\n|format = 1\n|date = 9 June 2019\n|time = 19:00 [[Japan Standard Time|JST]]\n|round = [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]\n|score = 2\u20130\n|report = https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2019/06/09/world/friendlies/japan/el-salvador/3006572/\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|JPN}}\n|goals1 = [[Kensuke Nagai|Nagai]] {{goal|19||42}}\n|team2 = {{fb|SLV}}\n|goals2 = \n|stadium = [[Hitomebore Stadium Miyagi]]\n|location = [[Rifu]], [[Miyagi Prefecture|Miyagi]], [[Japan]]\n|attendance = \n|referee = [[Ma Ning (referee)|Ma Ning]] ([[Chinese Football Association|China]])\n|result = L\n}}\n{{football box collapsible\n|format = 1\n|date = 17 June 2019\n|time = 18:00 [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|round = [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup Group C|CONCACAF Gold Cup]]\n|score = 0\u20131\n|report = https://www.goldcup.org/en/gold-cup/game-detail/476767\n|team1 = {{fb-rt|CUW}}\n|goals1 = \n|team2 = {{fb|SLV}}\n|goals2 = [[Nelson Bonilla|Bonilla]] {{goal|45+1}}\n|stadium = [[Independence Park (Jamaica)|Independence Park]]\n|location = [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]], [[Jamaica]]\n|attendance = \n|referee = Walter L\u00f3pez ([[National Football Federation of Guatemala|Guatemala]]