{"title_page": "Kishkino, Ustyuzhensky District, Vologda Oblast", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Kishkino\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u041a\u0438\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Ustyuzhensky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|58|57|N|35|53|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/ustyuzhenskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0423\u0441\u0442\u044e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Kishkino''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u0438\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Mezzhenskoye Rural Settlement, [[Ustyuzhensky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 5 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> There are 2 streets.\n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Ustyuzhna]] is 43&nbsp;km, to Dolotskoye is 6&nbsp;km. Dolotskoye is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Ustyuzhensky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Ustyuzhensky District]]\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Kishkino\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u041a\u0438\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Ustyuzhensky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|58|57|N|35|53|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/ustyuzhenskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0423\u0441\u0442\u044e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Kishkino''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u0438\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Mezzhenskoye Rural Settlement, [[Ustyuzhensky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 5 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> There are 2 streets.\n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Ustyuzhna]] is 43&nbsp;km, to Dolotskoye is 6&nbsp;km. Dolotskoye is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Ustyuzhensky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Ustyuzhensky District]]\n\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kishkino,_Ustyuzhensky_District,_Vologda_Oblast"}
{"title_page": "June Almeida", "text_new": "{{under construction|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Scottish virologist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = June Dalziel Almeida\n| image             = June_Dalziel_Almeida_died_2007.png\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = June Dalziel Hart\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1930|10|05|df=yes|}}\n| birth_place       = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|2007|12|1|1930|10|5|df=yes}}\n| death_place       = [[Bexhill-on-Sea|Bexhill]], England\n| resting_place     = \n| residence         = \n| nationality  = [[Scotland|Scottish]]\n| citizenship  = [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]]\n| fields            = [[Virology]], [[histopathology]]\n| workplaces        = [[Glasgow Royal Infirmary]], [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], [[Ontario Cancer Institute]], [[Royal Postgraduate Medical School]], [[Wellcome Research Laboratory]]\n| alma_mater        = \n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = Pioneer of [[Immunostaining#Immuno-electron microscopy|immuno-electron microscopy]]\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = [[Albert Kapikian]]\n| awards            = \n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = {{marriage|Enriques Rosalio (Henry) Almeida|1954|}} <br> {{marriage|Phillip Samuel Gardner|1982|1994}} (deceased)\n| children = 1\n}}\n\n'''June Dalziel Almeida''' (5 October 1930 \u2013 1 December 2007) was a Scottish [[Virology|virologist]] who, with little formal education, became a Doctor of Science and a pioneer in virus imaging, identification and diagnosis.<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/> She discovered a new type of [[coronavirus]]. The [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) published her ''Manual for rapid laboratory viral diagnosis'' in 1979.\n\n==Early life ==\nJune Dalziel Hart was born on 5 October 1930 at 10 Duntroon Street, [[Glasgow]] to Jane Dalziel (n\u00e9e Steven) and Harry Leonard Hart, a bus driver.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\">{{Cite journal| volume = 336| issue = 7659| pages = 1511| last = Almeida| first = Joyce| title = June Almeida (n\u00e9e Hart)| journal = [[British Medical Journal]] (BMJ)| publisher= [[BMJ Group]] | access-date = 18 April 2020| date = 28 June 2008| url = https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2440895/| pmc = 2440895 |issn=1511.1\u20131511 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.a434}}</ref>{{rp|1511.1\u20131511}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/|title=The Times & The Sunday Times|website=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>   \n\n==Education==\nShe left school at 16 to work as a [[histopathology]]  technician at [[Glasgow Royal Infirmary]]. She then moved to [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]] to continue her career.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===Ontario Cancer Institute===\n\nAlmeida began her career at the [[Ontario Cancer Institute]] in Toronto, Canada as an [[Electron microscope|electronmicroscopist]].<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\nIn 1963 she was the first  of three authors, who co-published an article in the journal ''[[Science]]'', in which they identified virus-like particles in cancer patients' blood.<ref name=\"Science_Almeida_1963\">{{Cite journal| title = Virus-Like Particles in Blood of Two Acute Leukemia Patients | access-date = April 18, 2020| url = https://science.sciencemag.org/content/142/3598/1487 |title=Virus-Like Particles in Blood of Two Acute Leukemia Patients |first1=June D. |last1=Almeida |first2=Richard C. |last2=Hasselback |first3=Arthur W. |last3=Ham|journal=Science  |date=December 13, 1963 |volume=142 |number=3598 |pages= 1487-1489 |doi=10.1126/science.142.3598.1487 |pmid=14077540}}</ref>\n\nShe published the results of her work in which she had identified the viral structure of the coronavirus in 1964, using electron microscope techniques that she had developed. \n\n===St Thomas's Hospital Medical School===\n{{main|St Thomas's Hospital Medical School}}\n\nIn the next stage of her career, she continued the research begun in Ontario, at one of the oldest and most prestigious medical schools in the United Kingdom, \u2014[[London]]'s [[St Thomas's Hospital Medical School]]\u2014now part of [[King's College London]].\n\nHer research there included developing a method to better visualise viruses by using [[antibody|antibodies]] to aggregate them. At St Thomas, she worked on [[hepatitis B virus]] and the [[Common cold|cold viruses]].<ref name=odnb/>\n\n{{clear left}}\n[[File:Virus surrounded by a distinct 200 A long fringe by Almeida and Tyrrell 1966.png|left|thumb|Virus identified by Almeida 1966]]\nIn a 1966 ''[[Journal of General Virology]]'' article with  [[David Tyrrell (physician)|David Tyrrell]] as second author, they identified \"previously uncharacterized human respiratory viruses.\" Almeida and Tyrrell wrote that, \"The particles are pleomorphic, in the size range 800 to 1200 A, and are surrounded by a distinct 200 A long fringe. They are indistinguishable from the particles of avian infectious bronchitis.\"<ref name=\"JGV_Almeida_1966\">{{Cite journal|last=Almeida|first=June D.|last2=Tyrrell|first2=D. A. J.|date=1967|title=The Morphology of Three Previously Uncharacterized Human Respiratory Viruses that Grow in Organ Culture|journal=Journal of General Virology|volume=1|issue=2|pages=175\u2013178|doi=10.1099/0022-1317-1-2-175|pmid=4293939|issn=0022-1317}}</ref>\n\nAlmeida produced the first images of the [[rubella]] virus using immune-electronmicroscopy.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Brilliant! Scottish inventors, innovators, scientists and engineers who changed the world|last=Paterson|first=Andrew|publisher=Austin Macauley|year=2017|isbn=9781786294357|location=London|pages=577}}</ref>. \n\n[[David Tyrrell (physician)|David Tyrrell]] and Almeida worked on characterising a new type of [[coronavirus]].<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\">{{Cite book | last1 = Booss |first1=John |authorlink=John Boos| last2 = August |first2=Marilyn J. | title = To catch a virus | publisher = ASM Press | location = Washington, DC | access-date = 18 April 2020| year = 2013 | url=https://archive.org/details/tocatchvirus0000boos/page/217 | isbn = 978-1-55581-507-3 }}</ref>{{rp|209}}\n\nThis family includes the [[SARS virus]] and the SARS-CoV2 virus that causes [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].\n\nAlmeida followed Waterson to the [[Royal Postgraduate Medical School|Postgraduate Medical School]] in London where her contributions to articles were recognised by her award of a Doctorate. She finished her career at the [[Wellcome Institute]].<ref name=odnb>{{cite web |first1=J. E. |last1=Banatvala |series=Almeida, June Dalziel (1930\u20132007) |title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] (OUP)|date= January 2011 |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/99332 |access-date= 18 October 2012}}</ref> While working for Wellcome she was named on several patents in the field of imaging viruses.<ref>[http://patent.ipexl.com/inventor/Almeida_June_Dalziel_1.html Almeida, June Dalziel], patents, accessed October 2012</ref>\n\n==Influences== \n\nIn 1970, [[Albert Kapikian]] studied Almeida's techniques in the United Kingdom for six months in order to use her techniques in the identification of a cause of non-bacterial gastroenteritis \u2013 the [[Norwalk virus]].<ref name=odnb/>\n\nChinese scientists used her work to identify [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] and her work, which was credited with assisting the early identification of the virus, according to professor [[Hugh Pennington]] .<ref name=\"heraldscotland\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18289806.june-almeida-tribute-scotlands-forgotten-hero-coronavirus/|title=June Almeida, tribute to Scotland's forgotten hero of the coronavirus|newspaper=Herald Scotland|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\nAfter retiring from Wellcome Institute, she returned in an advisory role in the late 1980s when she helped take novel pictures of the [[HIV virus]].<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\n==Publications==\nHer publications include the 1979 ''Manual for rapid laboratory viral diagnosis'' for the [[World Health Organisation]].<ref name=\"WHO_Almeida_1979\">{{Cite web|url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/offset/WHO_OFFSET_47.pdf|publisher=World Health Organization (WHO) |title=Manual for rapid laboratory viral diagnosis|date=1979}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy and coronavirus ==\n\nFollowing the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 COVID-19 pandemic]], her research came to notice again.<ref name=\"NatGeo\">{{cite news |last1=Combs |first1=Sydney |title=She Discovered Coronaviruses Decades Ago\u2014But Got Little Recognition |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/history/2020/04/june-almeida-discovered-coronaviruses-decades-ago-little-recognition/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |agency=National Geographic |publisher=National Geographic Society |date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> The BBC described Almedia as \"the woman who discovered the first [[coronavirus]].\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-52278716|title=The woman who discovered the first coronavirus|date=2020-04-15|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Professor [[Hugh Pennington]] noted that the Chinese had used her techniques to identify [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] and her work had helped the early identification.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18289806.june-almeida-tribute-scotlands-forgotten-hero-coronavirus/|title=June Almeida, tribute to Scotland's forgotten hero of the coronavirus|website=HeraldScotland|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAlmeida moved to Toronto, Ontario and worked at the Cancer Institute after her marriage on December 11, 1954 to Enrique Rosalio (Henry) Almeida (1913\u20131993), a Venezuelan artist with whom she had a daughter, Joyce.  Almeida died in [[Bexhill-on-Sea|Bexhill]] from a heart attack in 2007.<ref name=odnb/>\n\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Timeline of women in science]]\n\n==References==\n{{Scholia}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Almeida, June Dalziel}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:British virologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish scientists]]\n[[Category:British women biologists]]\n[[Category:Scottish women scientists]]\n[[Category:Wellcome Trust]]\n[[Category:20th-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:Women virologists]]\n", "text_old": "{{under construction|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Scottish virologist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = June Dalziel Almeida\n| image             = June_Dalziel_Almeida_died_2007.png\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = June Dalziel Hart\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1930|10|05|df=yes|}}\n| birth_place       = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|2007|12|1|1930|10|5|df=yes}}\n| death_place       = [[Bexhill-on-Sea|Bexhill]], England\n| resting_place     = \n| residence         = \n| nationality  = [[Scotland|Scottish]]\n| citizenship  = [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]]\n| fields            = [[Virology]], [[histopathology]]\n| workplaces        = [[Glasgow Royal Infirmary]], [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], [[Ontario Cancer Institute]], [[Royal Postgraduate Medical School]], [[Wellcome Research Laboratory]]\n| alma_mater        = \n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = Pioneer of [[Immunostaining#Immuno-electron microscopy|immuno-electron microscopy]]\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = [[Albert Kapikian]]\n| awards            = \n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = {{marriage|Enriques Rosalio (Henry) Almeida|1954|}} <br> {{marriage|Phillip Samuel Gardner|1982|1994}} (deceased)\n| children = 1\n}}\n\n'''June Dalziel Almeida''' (5 October 1930 \u2013 1 December 2007) was a Scottish [[Virology|virologist]] who, with little formal education, became a Doctor of Science and a pioneer in virus imaging, identification and diagnosis.<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\"/> She discovered a new type of [[coronavirus]]. The [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) published her ''Manual for rapid laboratory viral diagnosis'' in 1979.\n\n==Early life ==\nJune Dalziel Hart was born on 5 October 1930 at 10 Duntroon Street, [[Glasgow]] to Jane Dalziel (n\u00e9e Steven) and Harry Leonard Hart, a bus driver.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\">{{Cite journal| volume = 336| issue = 7659| pages = 1511| last = Almeida| first = Joyce| title = June Almeida (n\u00e9e Hart)| journal = [[British Medical Journal]] (BMJ)| publisher= [[BMJ Group]] | access-date = 18 April 2020| date = 28 June 2008| url = https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2440895/| pmc = PMC2440895 |issn=1511.1\u20131511 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.a434}}</ref>{{rp|1511.1\u20131511}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/|title=The Times & The Sunday Times|website=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>   \n\n==Education==\nShe left school at 16 to work as a [[histopathology]]  technician at [[Glasgow Royal Infirmary]]. She then moved to [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]] to continue her career.<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===Ontario Cancer Institute===\n\nAlmeida began her career at the [[Ontario Cancer Institute]] in Toronto, Canada as an [[Electron microscope|electronmicroscopist]].<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\nIn 1963 she was the first  of three authors, who co-published an article in the journal ''[[Science]]'', in which they identified virus-like particles in cancer patients' blood.<ref name=\"Science_Almeida_1963\">{{Cite journal| title = Virus-Like Particles in Blood of Two Acute Leukemia Patients | access-date = April 18, 2020| url = https://science.sciencemag.org/content/142/3598/1487 |title=Virus-Like Particles in Blood of Two Acute Leukemia Patients |first1=June D. |last1=Almeida |first2=Richard C. |last2=Hasselback |first3=Arthur W. |last3=Ham|journal=Science  |date=December 13, 1963 |volume=142 |number=3598 |pages= 1487-1489 |doi=10.1126/science.142.3598.1487 |pmid=14077540}}</ref>\n\nShe published the results of her work in which she had identified the viral structure of the coronavirus in 1964, using electron microscope techniques that she had developed. \n\n===St Thomas's Hospital Medical School===\n{{main|St Thomas's Hospital Medical School}}\n\nIn the next stage of her career, she continued the research begun in Ontario, at one of the oldest and most prestigious medical schools in the United Kingdom, \u2014[[London]]'s [[St Thomas's Hospital Medical School]]\u2014now part of [[King's College London]].\n\nHer research there included developing a method to better visualise viruses by using [[antibody|antibodies]] to aggregate them. At St Thomas, she worked on [[hepatitis B virus]] and the [[Common cold|cold viruses]].<ref name=odnb/>\n\n{{clear left}}\n[[File:Virus surrounded by a distinct 200 A long fringe by Almeida and Tyrrell 1966.png|left|thumb|Virus identified by Almeida 1966]]\nIn a 1966 ''[[Journal of General Virology]]'' article with  [[David Tyrrell (physician)|David Tyrrell]] as second author, they identified \"previously uncharacterized human respiratory viruses.\" Almeida and Tyrrell wrote that, \"The particles are pleomorphic, in the size range 800 to 1200 A, and are surrounded by a distinct 200 A long fringe. They are indistinguishable from the particles of avian infectious bronchitis.\"<ref name=\"JGV_Almeida_1966\">{{Cite journal|last=Almeida|first=June D.|last2=Tyrrell|first2=D. A. J.|date=1967|title=The Morphology of Three Previously Uncharacterized Human Respiratory Viruses that Grow in Organ Culture|journal=Journal of General Virology|volume=1|issue=2|pages=175\u2013178|doi=10.1099/0022-1317-1-2-175|pmid=4293939|issn=0022-1317}}</ref>\n\nAlmeida produced the first images of the [[rubella]] virus using immune-electronmicroscopy.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Brilliant! Scottish inventors, innovators, scientists and engineers who changed the world|last=Paterson|first=Andrew|publisher=Austin Macauley|year=2017|isbn=9781786294357|location=London|pages=577}}</ref>. \n\n[[David Tyrrell (physician)|David Tyrrell]] and Almeida worked on characterising a new type of [[coronavirus]].<ref name=\"Booss_August_2013\">{{Cite book | last1 = Booss |first1=John |authorlink=John Boos| last2 = August |first2=Marilyn J. | title = To catch a virus | publisher = ASM Press | location = Washington, DC | access-date = 18 April 2020| year = 2013 | url=https://archive.org/details/tocatchvirus0000boos/page/217 | isbn = 978-1-55581-507-3 }}</ref>{{rp|209}}\n\nThis family includes the [[SARS virus]] and the SARS-CoV2 virus that causes [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].\n\nAlmeida followed Waterson to the [[Royal Postgraduate Medical School|Postgraduate Medical School]] in London where her contributions to articles were recognised by her award of a Doctorate. She finished her career at the [[Wellcome Institute]].<ref name=odnb>{{cite web |first1=J. E. |last1=Banatvala |series=Almeida, June Dalziel (1930\u20132007) |title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] (OUP)|date= January 2011 |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/99332 |access-date= 18 October 2012}}</ref> While working for Wellcome she was named on several patents in the field of imaging viruses.<ref>[http://patent.ipexl.com/inventor/Almeida_June_Dalziel_1.html Almeida, June Dalziel], patents, accessed October 2012</ref>\n\n==Influences== \n\nIn 1970, [[Albert Kapikian]] studied Almeida's techniques in the United Kingdom for six months in order to use her techniques in the identification of a cause of non-bacterial gastroenteritis \u2013 the [[Norwalk virus]].<ref name=odnb/>\n\nChinese scientists used her work to identify [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] and her work, which was credited with assisting the early identification of the virus, according to professor [[Hugh Pennington]] .<ref name=\"heraldscotland\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18289806.june-almeida-tribute-scotlands-forgotten-hero-coronavirus/|title=June Almeida, tribute to Scotland's forgotten hero of the coronavirus|newspaper=Herald Scotland|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\nAfter retiring from Wellcome Institute, she returned in an advisory role in the late 1980s when she helped take novel pictures of the [[HIV virus]].<ref name=\"BMJ_Obit_20080418\"/>\n\n==Publications==\nHer publications include the 1979 ''Manual for rapid laboratory viral diagnosis'' for the [[World Health Organisation]].<ref name=\"WHO_Almeida_1979\">{{Cite web|url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/offset/WHO_OFFSET_47.pdf|publisher=World Health Organization (WHO) |title=Manual for rapid laboratory viral diagnosis|date=1979}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy and coronavirus ==\n\nFollowing the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 COVID-19 pandemic]], her research came to notice again.<ref name=\"NatGeo\">{{cite news |last1=Combs |first1=Sydney |title=She Discovered Coronaviruses Decades Ago\u2014But Got Little Recognition |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/history/2020/04/june-almeida-discovered-coronaviruses-decades-ago-little-recognition/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |agency=National Geographic |publisher=National Geographic Society |date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> The BBC described Almedia as \"the woman who discovered the first [[coronavirus]].\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-52278716|title=The woman who discovered the first coronavirus|date=2020-04-15|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Professor [[Hugh Pennington]] noted that the Chinese had used her techniques to identify [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] and her work had helped the early identification.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18289806.june-almeida-tribute-scotlands-forgotten-hero-coronavirus/|title=June Almeida, tribute to Scotland's forgotten hero of the coronavirus|website=HeraldScotland|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAlmeida moved to Toronto, Ontario and worked at the Cancer Institute after her marriage on December 11, 1954 to Enrique Rosalio (Henry) Almeida (1913\u20131993), a Venezuelan artist with whom she had a daughter, Joyce.  Almeida died in [[Bexhill-on-Sea|Bexhill]] from a heart attack in 2007.<ref name=odnb/>\n\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Timeline of women in science]]\n\n==References==\n{{Scholia}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Almeida, June Dalziel}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:British virologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish scientists]]\n[[Category:British women biologists]]\n[[Category:Scottish women scientists]]\n[[Category:Wellcome Trust]]\n[[Category:20th-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:Women virologists]]\n", "name_user": "Oceanflynn", "label": "safe", "comment": "ref details", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/June_Almeida"}
{"title_page": "Korokolets", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Korokolets\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u041a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0446\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Settlement\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Ustyuzhensky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|58|56|N|36|54|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/ustyuzhenskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0423\u0441\u0442\u044e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Korokolets''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0446}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|settlement]]) in Lentyevskoye Rural Settlement, [[Ustyuzhensky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 9 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> There are 12 streets.\n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Ustyuzhna]] is 39&nbsp;km, to Lentyevo is 18&nbsp;km. Vanskoye is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Ustyuzhensky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Ustyuzhensky District]]\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Korokolets\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u041a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0446\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Settlement\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Ustyuzhensky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|58|56|N|36|54|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/ustyuzhenskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0423\u0441\u0442\u044e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Korokolets''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0446}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|settlement]]) in Lentyevskoye Rural Settlement, [[Ustyuzhensky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 9 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> There are 12 streets.\n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Ustyuzhna]] is 39&nbsp;km, to Lentyevo is 18&nbsp;km. Vanskoye is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Ustyuzhensky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Ustyuzhensky District]]\n\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Korokolets"}
{"title_page": "Georgi Seganov", "text_new": "{{short description|Bulgarian volleyball player}}\n{{Infobox volleyball biography\n| name          = Georgi Seganov\n| image         = Georgi Seganov (Legavolley 2018).jpg\n| caption       =\n| nationality   = {{flagicon|BUL}} [[Bulgaria|Bulgarian]]\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1993|6|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Razlog]], [[Bulgaria]]\n| height        = 1.98 m\n| weight        = 83 kg\n| spike         = 340 cm\n| block         = 325 cm\n| position      = Setter\n| currentclub   = {{flagicon|TUR}} [[Halkbank Ankara]]\n| currentnumber = 12\n| years         = 2014\u20132016<br> 2016\u20132018<br> 2018\u20132019<br> 2019\u2013\n| teams         = {{flagicon|BUL}} [[VC CSKA Sofia|CSKA Sofia]]<br> {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Argos Volley]]<br> {{flagicon|TUR}} [[Maliye Milli Piyango SK|Maliye Milli Piyango]]<br> {{flagicon|TUR}} [[Halkbank Ankara]]\n| nationalyears = 2014\u2013\n| nationalteam  = {{vb|BUL}}\n}}\n\n'''Georgi Seganov ''' ({{lang-bg|\u0413\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0438 \u0421\u0435\u0433\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432}}, born 10 June 1993) is a [[Bulgary|Bulgarian]] [[volleyball]] player, a member of the [[Bulgaria men's national volleyball team]] and [[Turkey|Turkish]] club [[Halkbank Ankara]]. He was part of the Bulgarian national team at the [[2014 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Championship|2014 FIVB World Championship]] in Poland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.argosvolley.it/in-regia-georgi-seganov/ |title=In regia Georgi Seganov |work=www.argosvolley.it |language=it |date=18 July 2016 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldofvolley.com/Latest_news/Italy/81399/.html |title=ITA M: Sora have renewed contract with Bulgarian setter |work=www.worldofvolley.com |date=9 March 2017 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.argosvolley.it/georgi-seganov-la-prima-partenza-in-casa-argos-volley/ |title=Georgi Seganov, la prima partenza in casa Argos Volley  |work=www.argosvolley.it |language=it |date=18 May 2018 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.halkbankspor.org.tr/Haber/Detail/55580 |title=Halkbanka ho\u015f geldin Georgi Seganov |work=www.halkbankspor.org.tr |language=tr |date=5 September 2019 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Sporting achievements==\n===Individually===\n* '''2016:''' [[2016 Memorial of Hubert Jerzy Wagner|Memorial of Hubert Jerzy Wagner]] \u2013 Best Setter\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.legavolley.it/player/SEG-GEO-93 leagavolley.it player profile] \n* [https://volleybox.net/georgi-seganov-p4132/clubs volleybox.net player profile]\n* [http://poland2014.fivb.org/en/competition/teams/bul%20bulgaria/team_roster 2014 FIVB World Championship \u2013 Team Bulgaria] \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seganov, Georgi}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:People from Razlog]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian expatriates in Italy]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Italy]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian expatriates in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Expatriate volleyball players in Turkey]]\n\n{{Bulgaria-volleyball-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Bulgarian volleyball player}}\n{{Infobox volleyball biography\n| name          = Georgi Seganov\n| image         = Georgi Seganov (Legavolley 2018).jpg\n| caption       =\n| nationality   = {{flagicon|BUL}} [[Bulgaria|Bulgarian]]\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1993|6|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Razlog]], [[Bulgaria]]\n| height        = 1.98 m\n| weight        = 83 kg\n| spike         = 340 cm\n| block         = 325 cm\n| position      = Setter\n| currentclub   = {{flagicon|TUR}} [[Halkbank Ankara]]\n| currentnumber = 12\n| years         = 2014\u20132016<br> 2016\u20132018<br> 2018\u20132019<br> 2019\u2013\n| teams         = {{flagicon|BUL}} [[VC CSKA Sofia|CSKA Sofia]]<br> {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Argos Volley]]<br> {{flagicon|TUR}} [[Maliye M