/troubles/the_troubles_article_01.shtml BBC Northern Ireland: The Troubles]\n* [http://www.wesleyjohnston.com/users/ireland/past/troubles/index.htm The Troubles \u2013 Statistical Analysis]\n*[http://www.peacewall-archive.net Peacewall Archive] \u2013 An archive of photos, maps, texts and links relating to Belfast's [[Peace lines]] \u2013 a legacy of 'The Troubles'\n* [https://wikileaks.org/wiki/UK_military_operations_in_Northern_Ireland_1969-2006_aka_Operation_Banner British Army Historical Document]\n* [[Linen Hall Library]] [https://web.archive.org/web/20130203185316/http://www.linenhall.com/northernIrelandPoliticalCollection.asp Northern Ireland Political Collection]\n* [https://www.c-span.org/video/?42686-1/irish-troubles ''Booknotes'' interview with J. Bowyer Bell on ''The Irish Troubles: A Generation of Violence, 1967\u20131992'', 6 June 1993.]\n* {{Internet Archive short film|id = gov.archives.arc.1633583|name = Ulster (1970)}}\n* [http://www.theirishstory.com/tag/the-troubles/ The Irish Story archive on the Troubles]\n* [http://www.sinnfein.org/releases/freedom.html The Conflict in Ireland \u2013 1991 Sinn F\u00e9in document]\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/report/1991/RAC.htm The Roots of Terrorism in Northern Ireland \u2013 1991 Global Security report]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24987465 Interview with undercover soldiers by BBC dated 21 November 2013]\n* [http://player.bfi.org.uk/film/watch-belfast-no-way-out-1970/ Belfast: No Way Out (1970) on BFI Player]\n* [http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch72.htm Timeline of events]\n\n{{The Troubles|state = collapsed}}\n{{Post-Cold War European conflicts}}\n{{Ireland topics}}\n{{1968 protests}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Paramilitaries of The Troubles\n|list1=\n{{PIRA}}\n{{OIRA/WP}}\n{{INLA/IRSP}}\n{{CIRA/RSF}}\n{{RIRA/32CSM}}\n{{Ulster Defence Association}}\n{{Ulster Volunteer Force}}\n{{Loyalist Volunteer Force}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Troubles, The}}\n[[Category:The Troubles (Northern Ireland)| ]]\n[[Category:The Troubles (Northern Ireland) by locality]]\n[[Category:1960s in Irish politics]]\n[[Category:1970s in Irish politics]]\n[[Category:1980s in Irish politics]]\n[[Category:1990s in Irish politics]]\n[[Category:Dirty wars]]\n[[Category:Guerrilla wars]]\n[[Category:History of Belfast]]\n[[Category:History of Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Politics of Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Ireland]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "Harvey Milligan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Troubles"}
{"title_page": "Dmitry Dolgopyat", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Dmitry Dolgopyat\n| image             = <!--(filename only)-->\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       = \n| nationality       = [[Russia]]n\n| fields            = [[Mathematics]]\n| workplaces        = [[University of Maryland]]\n| alma_mater        = [[Moscow State University]]<br>[[Princeton University]]\n| doctoral_advisor  = [[Yakov Sinai]]\n| known_for         = \n| awards            = [[Michael Brin Prize in Dynamical Systems]] (2009)\n}}\n\n'''Dmitry Dolgopyat''' is a [[Russian-American]] [[mathematician]] at the [[University of Maryland]] known for his research in [[dynamical system]]s.\n\nHe graduated from [[Moscow State School 57]] mathematical class in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sch57.ru/people/alumni/#y1989|title= Alumni list|publisher=Moscow School 57}}</ref> From 1989 to 1994, he was an undergraduate student at [[Moscow State University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.math.umd.edu/~dolgop/vita.html |title=Dmitry Dolgopyat. Resume. |date= |accessdate=2015-08-23}}</ref> From 1994 to 1997, he was enrolled in [[Princeton University]], where he earned a [[PhD]] under the guidance of [[Yakov Sinai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=14863 |title=The Mathematics Genealogy Project - Dmitry Dolgopyat |publisher=Genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu |date= |accessdate=2015-08-23}}</ref>\n\nHe was an invited speaker at the 2006 [[International Congress of Mathematicians]] in Madrid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mathunion.org/db/ICM/Speakers/SortedByLastname.php |title= ICM Plenary and Invited Speakers since 1897}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he was awarded the [[Michael Brin Prize in Dynamical Systems]] for his fundamental contributions to the theory of hyperbolic dynamics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.personal.psu.edu/axk29/BrinPrize2.html |title=2009 MICHAEL BRIN PRIZE IN DYNAMICAL SYSTEMS\n |date= |accessdate=2015-08-23}}</ref>\n\nDmitry Dolgopyat became openly gay when arriving is USA, something that he couldn't do in Russia, and is proud of it, although preferring not to become an activist of any sort.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dolgopyat, Dmitry}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Maryland, College Park faculty]]\n[[Category:Dynamical systems theorists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Russia-mathematician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Dmitry Dolgopyat\n| image             = <!--(filename only)-->\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       = \n| nationality       = [[Russia]]n\n| fields            = [[Mathematics]]\n| workplaces        = [[University of Maryland]]\n| alma_mater        = [[Moscow State University]]<br>[[Princeton University]]\n| doctoral_advisor  = [[Yakov Sinai]]\n| known_for         = \n| awards            = [[Michael Brin Prize in Dynamical Systems]] (2009)\n}}\n\n'''Dmitry Dolgopyat''' is a [[Russian-American]] [[mathematician]] at the [[University of Maryland]] known for his research in [[dynamical system]]s.\n\nHe graduated from [[Moscow State School 57]] mathematical class in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sch57.ru/people/alumni/#y1989|title= Alumni list|publisher=Moscow School 57}}</ref> From 1989 to 1994, he was an undergraduate student at [[Moscow State University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.math.umd.edu/~dolgop/vita.html |title=Dmitry Dolgopyat. Resume. |date= |accessdate=2015-08-23}}</ref> From 1994 to 1997, he was enrolled in [[Princeton University]], where he earned a [[PhD]] under the guidance of [[Yakov Sinai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=14863 |title=The Mathematics Genealogy Project - Dmitry Dolgopyat |publisher=Genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu |date= |accessdate=2015-08-23}}</ref>\n\nHe was an invited speaker at the 2006 [[International Congress of Mathematicians]] in Madrid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mathunion.org/db/ICM/Speakers/SortedByLastname.php |title= ICM Plenary and Invited Speakers since 1897}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he was awarded the [[Michael Brin Prize in Dynamical Systems]] for his fundamental contributions to the theory of hyperbolic dynamics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.personal.psu.edu/axk29/BrinPrize2.html |title=2009 MICHAEL BRIN PRIZE IN DYNAMICAL SYSTEMS\n |date= |accessdate=2015-08-23}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dolgopyat, Dmitry}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Maryland, College Park faculty]]\n[[Category:Dynamical systems theorists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Russia-mathematician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2804:431:c7c6:d161:e19e:f1e3:ccbb:b124", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dmitry_Dolgopyat"}
{"title_page": "2020 Utah gubernatorial election", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2020 Utah gubernatorial election\n| country            = Utah\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = yes\n| previous_election  = 2016 Utah gubernatorial election\n| previous_year      = 2016\n| next_election      = 2024 Utah gubernatorial election\n| next_year          = 2024\n| election_date      = November 3, 2020\n| image1             = \n| nominee1           = TBD\n| party1             = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1      = '''347'''\n| percentage1        = 63%\n| image2             = \n| nominee2           = TBD\n| party2             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2      = 146\n| percentage2        = 37%\n| title              = Governor\n| before_election    = [[Gary Herbert]]\n| before_party       = Republican Party (United States)\n| elected governor=  \n| after party=}}\n{{ElectionsUT}}\n\nThe '''2020 Utah gubernatorial election''' will be held on November 3, 2020, to elect the [[Governor of Utah]], concurrently with the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 U.S. presidential election]], as well as [[United States Senate elections, 2020|elections]] to the [[United States Senate]] and elections to the [[United States House of Representatives]] and various [[United States elections, 2020#State elections|state]] and local elections. Although incumbent [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Governor [[Gary Herbert]] is eligible to run for re-election to a third full term, he initially announced shortly after being re-elected in 2016 that he would not run again, but indicated in January 2019 that he was open to the possibility of running again before ultimately deciding to retire and endorse his Lieutenant Governor [[Spencer Cox (politician)|Spencer Cox]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gehrke|first1=Robert|title=Herbert wins his 3rd election as Utah governor|url=http://www.sltrib.com/home/4559987-155/herbert-appears-headed-to-victory-in|accessdate=21 November 2016|publisher=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=8 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"neversaynever\">{{cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900053102/utah-gov-gary-herbert-possible-re-election-bid.html|title=About face? Utah Gov. Gary Herbert says 'never say never' about possible re-election bid|last1=O'Donoghue|first1=Amy Joi|date=January 29, 2019|newspaper=Deseret News|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Reasons\">{{cite news |last1=O'Donoghue |first1=Amy Joi |title=Here are the reasons Utah Lt. Gov. Spencer Cox says he's running for governor in 2020 |url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900070594/spencer-cox-2020-utah-governor-race.html |accessdate=15 May 2019 |work=Deseret News |date=May 14, 2019}}</ref> Utah has not had a Democratic governor since [[Scott M. Matheson]] left office in January 1985. This is the second longest active streak of one-party leadership, trailing only [[South Dakota]], which has not had a Democratic governor since [[Harvey L. Wollman]] left office in 1979.<ref name=\"UT\">{{cite news |last1=Wood |first1=Benjamin |title=achary Moses, a Democratic candidate for governor, wants to break up Republican control of Utah and build a space port |url=https://www.sltrib.com/news/politics/2019/07/19/zachary-moses-democratic/ |accessdate=29 August 2019 |work=Salt Lake Tribune |date=July 19, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"SD\">{{cite news |last1=Scott |first1=Dylan |title=Kristi Noem elected first woman governor of South Dakota |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/11/7/18055928/midterm-election-results-south-dakota-governor-kristi-noem-winner |accessdate=August 26, 2019 |work=Vox |date=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe winner of the election will be the first non-incumbent gubernatorial candidate to be elected since [[Jon Huntsman Jr.]] in 2004.  The primary is scheduled for June 23, 2020. The filing deadline was on March 19, 2020.\n\n==Republican primary==\n===Candidates===\n====Declared====\n*Jeff Burningham, businessman<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sltrib.com/news/politics/2019/09/10/jeff-burningham-declares/|title=Jeff Burningham declares his candidacy for Utah governor|last=Wood|first=Benjamin|website=sltrib.com|language=en-us|access-date=2019-09-28}}</ref>\n**[[Dan McCay]], state senator<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dudley |first1=Graham |title=Jeff Burningham names state Sen. Dan McCay as running mate |url=https://www.ksl.com/article/46737153/jeff-burningham-names-state-sen-dan-mccay-as-running-mate |website=KSL.com |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n*Jason Christensen, activist<ref name=\"UTGOVC\">{{cite web |last1=Vandenack |first1=Tim |title=Weber County commission race draws 3 hopefuls as candidate filing period opens |url=https://www.standard.net/news/government/weber-county-commission-race-draws-hopefuls-as-candidate-filing-period/article_9fac1642-c55b-5a12-b98c-629525aa26c4.html |website=Standard-Examiner |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n** Drew Chamberlain<ref>{{cite web |last1=Roche |first1=Lisa Riley |title=Gubernatorial candidate Greg Hughes names southern Utah commissioner as running mate |url=https://www.deseret.com/utah/2020/4/14/21220814/gubernatorial-candidate-greg-hughes-names-southern-utah-commissioner-as-running-mate |website=Deseret News |language=en |date=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Spencer Cox (politician)|Spencer Cox]], [[Lieutenant Governor of Utah]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sltrib.com/news/politics/2019/05/14/lt-gov-spencer-cox/|title=Lt. Gov. Spencer Cox announces he is running for Utah governor, vows a \u2018different,\u2019 positive campaign|website=The Salt Lake Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox13now.com/2019/05/14/spencer-cox-announces-run-for-utah-governor-in-2020/|title=Lt. Gov. Spencer Cox announces run for Utah governor in 2020|date=2019-05-14|website=fox13now.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://