ions]] to the [[United States Senate]] and elections to the [[United States House of Representatives]] and various [[United States elections, 2020#State elections|state]] and local elections. Although incumbent [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Governor [[Gary Herbert]] is eligible to run for re-election to a third full term, he initially announced shortly after being re-elected in 2016 that he would not run again, but indicated in January 2019 that he was open to the possibility of running again before ultimately deciding to retire and endorse his Lieutenant Governor [[Spencer Cox (politician)|Spencer Cox]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gehrke|first1=Robert|title=Herbert wins his 3rd election as Utah governor|url=http://www.sltrib.com/home/4559987-155/herbert-appears-headed-to-victory-in|accessdate=21 November 2016|publisher=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=8 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"neversaynever\">{{cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900053102/utah-gov-gary-herbert-possible-re-election-bid.html|title=About face? Utah Gov. Gary Herbert says 'never say never' about possible re-election bid|last1=O'Donoghue|first1=Amy Joi|date=January 29, 2019|newspaper=Deseret News|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Reasons\">{{cite news |last1=O'Donoghue |first1=Amy Joi |title=Here are the reasons Utah Lt. Gov. Spencer Cox says he's running for governor in 2020 |url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900070594/spencer-cox-2020-utah-governor-race.html |accessdate=15 May 2019 |work=Deseret News |date=May 14, 2019}}</ref> Utah has not had a Democratic governor since [[Scott M. Matheson]] left office in January 1985. This is the second longest active streak of one-party leadership, trailing only [[South Dakota]], which has not had a Democratic governor since [[Harvey L. Wollman]] left office in 1979.<ref name=\"UT\">{{cite news |last1=Wood |first1=Benjamin |title=achary Moses, a Democratic candidate for governor, wants to break up Republican control of Utah and build a space port |url=https://www.sltrib.com/news/politics/2019/07/19/zachary-moses-democratic/ |accessdate=29 August 2019 |work=Salt Lake Tribune |date=July 19, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"SD\">{{cite news |last1=Scott |first1=Dylan |title=Kristi Noem elected first woman governor of South Dakota |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/11/7/18055928/midterm-election-results-south-dakota-governor-kristi-noem-winner |accessdate=August 26, 2019 |work=Vox |date=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe winner of the election will be the first non-incumbent gubernatorial candidate to be elected since [[Jon Huntsman Jr.]] in 2004.  The primary is scheduled for June 23, 2020. The filing deadline was on March 19, 2020.\n\n==Republican primary==\n===Candidates===\n====Declared====\n*Jeff Burningham, businessman<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sltrib.com/news/politics/2019/09/10/jeff-burningham-declares/|title=Jeff Burningham declares his candidacy for Utah governor|last=Wood|first=Benjamin|website=sltrib.com|language=en-us|access-date=2019-09-28}}</ref>\n**[[Dan McCay]], state senator<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dudley |first1=Graham |title=Jeff Burningham names state Sen. Dan McCay as running mate |url=https://www.ksl.com/article/46737153/jeff-burningham-names-state-sen-dan-mccay-as-running-mate |website=KSL.com |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n*Jason Christensen, activist<ref name=\"UTGOVC\">{{cite web |last1=Vandenack |first1=Tim |title=Weber County commission race draws 3 hopefuls as candidate filing period opens |url=https://www.standard.net/news/government/weber-county-commission-race-draws-hopefuls-as-candidate-filing-period/article_9fac1642-c55b-5a12-b98c-629525aa26c4.html |website=Standard-Examiner |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n** Drew Chamberlain<ref>{{cite web |last1=Roche |first1=Lisa Riley |title=Gubernatorial candidate Greg Hughes names southern Utah commissioner as running mate |url=https://www.deseret.com/utah/2020/4/14/21220814/gubernatorial-candidate-greg-