d-predictions/governor/|title=We rated every gubernatorial race in 2020. Here's who we think will win.|website= Poltico|access-date= November 19, 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#f66\" |{{sort|098|Safe R}}\n|November 19, 2019\n|}\n\n===Results===\n{{Election box begin \n| title = 2020 Utah gubernatorial election\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link \n| candidate  = TBA\n| party      = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes      = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link \n| candidate  = TBA\n| party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes      = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total \n| votes      = \n| percentage = 100.0%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Notes==\n;Additional candidates\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n;Official campaign websites\n* [https://jeffburningham.com/ Jeff Burningham (R) for Governor]\n* [https://www.votecox.com/ Spencer Cox (R) for Governor]\n* [https://greghughes.com/ Greg Hughes (R) for Governor]\n* [https://huntsman2020.com/ Jon Huntsman Jr. (R) for Governor]\n* [https://aimeeforgovernor.com/ Aimee Winder Newton (R) for Governor]\n* [https://zachmoses.com/ Zachary Moses (D) for Governor]\n* [https://petersonforutah.com/ Christopher Peterson (D) for Governor]\n* [https://www.wrightutah.com/ Thomas Wright (R) for Governor]\n\n{{United States elections, 2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 United States gubernatorial elections|Utah]]\n[[Category:Utah gubernatorial elections|2020]]\n[[Category:2020 Utah elections|Governor]]\n", "name_user": "PutItOnAMap", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_Utah_gubernatorial_election"}
{"title_page": "Taffeta", "text_new": "[[File:Woman's Dress LACMA M.2007.211.35 (3 of 7).jpg|thumb|right|200px|Detail of a c. 1880 dress made of silk taffeta]]\n'''Taffeta''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t|\u00e6|f|\u1d7b|t|\u0259}}; archaically spelled '''taffety''') is a crisp, smooth, [[Plain weave|plain woven]] [[fabric]] made from [[silk]] or [[cuprammonium rayon]]s as well as [[cellulose acetate|acetate]] and [[polyester]]. The word is [[Persian language|Persian]] (\u062a\u0627\u0641\u062a\u0647) in origin and means \"twisted woven\". It is considered to be a \"high-end\" fabric, suitable for use in [[ball gown]]s, [[wedding dress]]es, and in interior decoration for [[curtain]]s or [[wallcovering]]s. It is also widely used in the manufacture of corsets and corsetry: it yields a more starched-like type of cloth that holds its shape better than many other fabrics. An extremely thin, crisp type of taffeta is called '''paper taffeta'''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Shaeffer|first1=Claire|title=Claire Shaeffer's fabric sewing guide|date=2008|publisher=Krause Publications|location=Cincinnati, Ohio|isbn=9781440223426|edition=2nd|url=https://archive.org/details/claireshaeffersf0000shae|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/claireshaeffersf0000shae/page/246 246]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Stevenson|editor1-first=Angus|title=Oxford dictionary of English.|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York, NY|isbn=9780199571123|page=1286|edition=3rd|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=anecAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1286#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\nThere are two distinct types of silk taffeta: yarn-[[dyed]] and piece-dyed. Piece-dyed taffeta is often used in [[lining (sewing)|linings]] and is quite soft. Yarn-dyed taffeta is much stiffer and is often used in evening dresses. [[Shot silk]] taffeta was one of the most highly sought forms of [[Byzantine silk]], and may have been the fabric known as ''purpura''.<ref>Dodwell, C.R.; ''[https://archive.org/details/anglosaxonartnew00dodw/page/147 Anglo-Saxon Art, A New Perspective]'', pp. 145-150, 1982, Manchester UP, {{ISBN|0-7190-0926-X}} (US edn. Cornell, 1985)</ref>\n\n==Production==\nModern taffeta was first woven in Italy and France and until the 1950s in Japan. [[Warp printing|Warp-printed]] taffeta or ''chin\u00e9'', mainly made in France from the eighteenth century onwards, is sometimes called \"pompadour taffeta\" after [[Madame de Pompadour]].<ref name=kyoto>{{cite book|last=Fukai|first=Akiko|title=Fashion : the collection of the Kyoto Costume Institute : a history from the 18th to the 20th century |year=2002 |publisher=Taschen |location=K\u00f6ln [etc.] |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ARLmnMFZ9rcC&pg=PA56&lpg=PA56&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false |isbn=9783822812068|pages=56}}</ref> Today most raw silk taffeta is produced in India and Pakistan. There, even in the modern period, [[handloom]]s were long widely used, but since the 1990s it has been produced on mechanical [[loom]]s in the [[Bangalore]] area. From the 1970s until the 1990s, the [[Jiangsu]] province of China produced fine silk taffetas: these were less flexible than those from Indian mills, however, which continue to dominate production. Other countries in Southeast Asia and the Middle East also produce silk taffeta, but these products are not yet equal in quality or competitiveness to those from India. The most deluxe taffetas, however, are still woven in France, Italy, Russia, and the United Kingdom.{{cn|date=December 2015}}\n\n==Historical and current uses==\nTaffeta has seen use for purposes other than clothing fabric, including the following:\n\n* On November 4, 1782, taffeta was used by [[Joseph Montgolfier]] of France to construct a small, cube-shaped [[balloon]]. This was the beginning of many experiments using taffeta balloons by the Montgolfier brothers, and led to the first known human flight in a lighter-than-air craft.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} \n* Synthetic fibre forms of taffeta have been used to simulate the structure of blood vessels.<ref>{{cite journal|pmid=13467673 | volume=105 | issue=3 | title=Heat sealed dacron taffeta blood vessel replacement |date=September 1957 | journal=Surg Gynecol Obstet | pages=370\u20134}}</ref>\n* [[Tabby cat]]s were so-named in the 1600s due to visual resemblance to a ''tabby'', a type of striped silk taffeta.<ref>{{cite web |title=Entry for tabby |url=https://www.etymonline.com/word/tabby |website=Online Etymology Dictionary |publisher=Douglas Harper |accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n* It was associated with [[prostitution]] during the [[English Renaissance]].<ref>[[David Scott Kastan]] (ed.). William Shakespeare. ''King Henry IV, Part 1''. [[Arden Shakespeare]] Third Series. London: [[Thompson Learning]], 2002, 150.</ref>  Examples include the references in [[William Shakespeare]]'s plays:  \"As fit as ten [[Groat (coin)|groats]] is for the hand of an attorney, as your [[\u00c9cu|French crown]] for your taffeta punk,\" says the Clown in ''[[All's Well That Ends Well]]'', [[Prince Hal]]'s reference to [[Sir John Falstaff]]'s \"fair hot wench in flame-coloured taffeta\" in ''[[Henry IV, Part 1]]'', Boyet's dismissal of \"Beauties no richer than rich taffeta\" in ''[[Love's Labour's Lost]]'', and Feste's insult in ''[[Twelfth Night, or What You Will]]'', \"The tailor make thy doublet of changeable taffeta, for thy mind is a very opal.\"\n\n==References==\nhttps://garmentmerchendising.com/what-is-a-taffeta-fabric/\n{{reflist}}\n*''Dictionary of Textiles'', Louis Harmuth. New York: Fairchild Publishing Company, 1915, p.&nbsp;184 (reprinted by Kessinger Publishing, 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-161-77823-6}})\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=_wE9AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA184&dq=taffeta+fabric&hl=en&ei=B0tzTJDxOJK4sQO25LSJDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CFEQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=taffeta%20fabric&f=false Google Books edition of \"Dictionary of Textiles\"]\n\n{{weaving}}\n{{fabric}}\n\n[[Category:Woven fabrics]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Woman's Dress LACMA M.2007.211.35 (3 of 7).jpg|thumb|right|200px|Detail of a c. 1880 dress made of silk taffeta]]\n'''Taffeta''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t|\u00e6|f|\u1d7b|t|\u0259}}; archaically spelled '''taffety''') is a crisp, smooth, [[Plain weave|plain woven]] [[fabric]] made from [[silk]] or [[cuprammonium rayon]]s as well as [[cellulose acetate|acetate]] and [[polyester]]. The word is [[Persian language|Persian]] (\u062a\u0627\u0641\u062a\u0647) in origin and means \"twisted woven\". It is considered to be a \"high-end\" fabric, suitable for use in [[ball gown]]s, [[wedding dress]]es, and in interior decoration for [[curtain]]s or [[wallcovering]]s. It is also widely used in the manufacture of corsets and corsetry: it yields a more starched-like type of cloth that holds its shape better than many other fabrics. An extremely thin, crisp type of taffeta is called '''paper taffeta'''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Shaeffer|first1=Claire|title=Claire Shaeffer's fabric sewing guide|date=2008|publisher=Krause Publications|location=Cincinnati, Ohio|isbn=9781440223426|edition=2nd|url=https://archive.org/details/claireshaeffersf0000shae|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/claireshaeffersf0000shae/page/246 246]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Stevenson|editor1-first=Angus|title=Oxford dictionary of English.|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York, NY|isbn=9780199571123|page=1286|edition=3rd|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=anecAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1286#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\nThere are two distinct types of silk taffeta: yarn-[[dyed]] and piece-dyed. Piece-dyed taffeta is often used in [[lining (sewing)|linings]] and is quite soft. Yarn-dyed taffeta is much stiffer and is often used in evening dresses. [[Shot silk]] taffeta was one of the most highly sought forms of [[Byzantine silk]], and may have been the fabric known as ''purpura''.<ref>Dodwell, C.R.; ''[https://archive.org/details/anglosaxonartnew00dodw/page/147 Anglo-Saxon Art, A New Perspective]'', pp. 145-150, 1982, Manchester UP, {{ISBN|0-7190-0926-X}} (US edn. Cornell, 1985)</ref>\n\n==Production==\nModern taffeta was first woven in Italy and France and until the 1950s in Japan. [[Warp printing|Warp-printed]] taffeta or ''chin\u00e9'', mainly made in France from the eighteenth century onwards, is sometimes called \"pompadour taffeta\" after [[Madame de Pompadour]].<ref name=kyoto>{{cite book|last=Fukai|first=Akiko|title=Fashion : the collection of the Kyoto Costume Institute : a history from the 18th to the 20th century |year=2002 |publisher=Taschen |location=K\u00f6ln [etc.] |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ARLmnMFZ9rcC&pg=PA56&lpg=PA56&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false |isbn=9783822812068|pages=56}}</ref> Today most raw silk taffeta is produced in India and Pakistan. There, even in the modern period, [[handloom]]s were long widely used, but since the 1990s it has been produced on mechanical [[loom]]s in the [[Bangalore]] area. From the 1970s until the 1990s, the [[Jiangsu]] province of China produced fine silk taffetas: these were less flexible than those from Indian mills, however, which continue to dominate production. Other countries in Southeast Asia and the Middle East also produce silk taffeta, but these products are not yet equal in quality or competitiveness to those from India. The most deluxe taffetas, however, are still woven in France, Italy, Russia, and the United Kingdom.{{cn|date=December 2015}}\n\n==Historical and current uses==\nTaffeta has seen use for purposes other than clothing fabric, including the following:\n\n* On November 4, 1782, taffeta was used by [[Joseph Montgolfier]] of France to construct a small, cube-shaped [[balloon]]. This was the beginning of many experiments using taffeta balloons by the Montgolfier brothers, and led to the first known human flight in a lighter-than-air craft.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} \n* Synthetic fibre forms of taffeta have been used to simulate the structure of blood vessels.<ref>{{cite journal|pmid=13467673 | volume=105 | issue=3 | title=Heat sealed dacron taffeta blood vessel replacement |date=September 1957 | journal=Surg Gynecol Obstet | pages=370\u20134}}</ref>\n* [[Tabby cat]]s were so-named in the 1600s due to visual resemblance to a ''tabby'', a type of striped silk taffeta.<ref>{{cite web |title=Entry for tabby |url=https://www.etymonline.com/word/tabby |website=Online Etymology Dictionary |publisher=Douglas Harper |accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n* It was associated with [[prostitution]] during the [[English Renaissance]].<ref>[[David Scott Kastan]] (ed.). William Shakespeare. ''King Henry IV, Part 1''. [[Arden Shakespeare]] Third Series. London: [[Thompson Learning]], 2002, 150.</ref>  Examples include the references in [[William Shakespeare]]'s plays:  \"As fit as ten [[Groat (coin)|groats]] is for the hand of an attorney, as your [[\u00c9cu|French crown]] for your taffeta punk,\" says the Clown in ''[[All's Well That Ends Well]]'', [[Prince Hal]]'s reference to [[Sir John Falstaff]]'s \"fair hot wench in flame-coloured taffeta\" in ''[[Henry IV, Part 1]]'', Boyet's dismissal of \"Beauties no richer than rich taffeta\" in ''[[Love's Labour's Lost]]'', and Feste's insult in ''[[Twelfth Night, or What You Will]]'', \"The tailor make thy doublet of changeable taffeta, for thy mind is a very opal.\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*''Dictionary of Textiles'', Louis Harmuth. New York: Fairchild Publishing Company, 1915, p.&nbsp;184 (reprinted by Kessinger Publishing, 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-161-77823-6}})\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=_wE9AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA184&dq=taffeta+fabric&hl=en&ei=B0tzTJDxOJK4sQO25LSJDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CFEQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=taffeta%20fabric&f=false Google Books edition of \"Dictionary of Textiles\"]\n\n{{weaving}}\n{{fabric}}\n\n[[Category:Woven fabrics]]\n", "name_user": "Yousafi13", "label": "safe", "comment": "i just added an other source for the reader from wikipedia", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taffeta"}
{"title_page": "Tropidelic", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Tropidelic\n| image           = [[File:2019 Press Photo (Michael Clare @mikecimages).jpg|200px]]\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| landscape       = yes\n| alt             = \n| caption         = ''The members of Tropidelic''\n| background      = group_or_band\n| alias           = \n| origin          = [[Cleveland, Ohio]]\n| genre           = [[Funk music|Funk]], [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Hip Hop music|Hip Hop]], [[Reggae music|Reggae]]\n| years_active    = 2008 - Present\n| label           = \n| associated_acts = \n| website         = http://www.tropidelic.com\n| current_members = Bobby Chronic, Derek McBryde, James Begin, Matthew Roads, Pags, Rex Larkman\n| past_members    = \n| module          = \n| module2         = \n| module3         = \n}}\n\n{{short description|American band}}\n<!--[[File:Live Action.jpeg|thumb|Tropidelic performing live in Cleveland, Ohio]]-->\n'''Tropidelic''' is an American band from [[Cleveland]], Ohio. Tropidelic infuses multiple genres into a style that's a blend of [[reggae rock]], [[hip-hop]] and high energy [[funk]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.axs.com/interview-tropidelic-frontman-matt-roads-talks-heavy-is-the-head-follo-132482 |website=[[AXS (company)]]|last=Cohen|first=Sari|date=10 August 2018|accessdate=31 May 2019|title=Interview: Tropidelic frontman Matt Roads talks \u2018Heavy Is The Head\u2019 follow-up and the upcoming InCuya Music Festival}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nTropidelic was formed by founding member Matthew Andrle and Kyle Cheuvront at [[Kent State University]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tribtoday.com/life/ticket/2019/05/tropidelic-heads-trop-the-block/ |website=[[Tribune Chronicle]]|last=Gatta|first=John Patrick|date=16 May 2019|accessdate=31 May 2019|title=Tropidelic heads Trop the Block}}</ref>, located in [[Kent, Ohio]], in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.clevescene.com/cleveland/meet-the-band-tropidelic/Content?oid=4815966 | title=Meet the Band: Tropidelic|website=[[Cleveland Scene]]|last=Niesel|first=Jeff|date=30 March 2016|accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref> They self-distributed over 10,000 free copies of their first self-produced EP, Rebirth of the Dope.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.clevescene.com/scene-and-heard/archives/2017/10/16/the-local-reggae-hip-hop-funk-act-tropidelic-makes-forthcoming-album-available-for-preorder |website=The Cleveland Scene |accessdate=18 February 2019|title=The Cleveland Reggae/Hip-Hop/Funk Act Tropidelic Makes Forthcoming Album Available for Preorder }}</ref> The band's second release, and first studio recording, was Tree City Exodus,<ref>{{cite web |title=Tropidelic to let audience preview new CD at the Robin Hood this Friday |author=Kristen Kotz |date=May 1, 2008 |url=http://www.kentwired.com/latest_updates/article_217a68a4-f4b5-5c6f-8f8c-9e0794b89109.html |website=Kent Wired |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> followed by Erie Tides & Irie Vibes. Over the years, the band has evolved through several member changes and the addition of a horn section, leading up to their first full-length album, All Heads Unite, being released in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.heraldpalladium.com/features/five-questions-tropidelic-brings-more-than-the-funk/article_494ef160-5d62-5a41-9a09-bf0cb7acbfc8.html | title=FIVE QUESTIONS: Tropidelic brings more than the funk}}</ref>\n\nSince the release of All Heads Unite, Tropidelic has released five additional albums.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tropidelic on Apple Music |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/artist/tropidelic/359319340 |publisher=iTunes Store |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> Their 2017 album, ''Heavy is the Head'', was released on Pepper's LAW Records<ref>{{cite web |title=First Watch: Tropidelic \u2013 Leviathan |url=https://rootfire.net/first-watch-tropidelic-leviathan/ |website=Rootfire |accessdate=18 February 2019|date=2017-10-26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/heavy-is-the-head/1264001615 |title=Heavy is the Head by Tropidelic |website=Apple Music |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> and reached #3 on the [[Billboard charts]] on December 2, 2017.<ref> {{Cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/music/tropidelic | title=Tropidelic}}</ref> Tropidelic's latest album, Here in the Heights was released on June 7, 2019 through [https://www.ineffablemusic.com/ Ineffable Music Group]. This full-length album features other notable artists such as Angelo Moore of [[Fishbone]], Howi Spangler of [[Ballyhoo!]], and [[Zach Deputy]], among others.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Niesel |first1=Jeff |title=Local Rockers Tropidelic to Release Their New Album on June 7 |url=https://www.clevescene.com/scene-and-heard/archives/2019/05/31/local-rockers-tropidelic-to-release-their-new-album-on-june-7 |website=Cleveland SCENE |accessdate=31 May  2019}}</ref> Here in the Heights peaked at #2 on the Billboard reggae charts on June 22, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tropidelic |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/tropidelic |website=Billboard |accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nTropidelic has been featured at [[Electric Forest Festival]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Past Lineup |url=https://electricforestfestival.com/history/past-lineups/ |website=Electric Forest |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> [[California Roots Music and Arts Festival|California Roots Music & Art Festival]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://californiarootsfestival.com/past-lineups |website=California Roots Music & Art Festival 2018 | title=Past Line-Ups |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> and [[Warped Tour]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eriereader.com/article/tropidelic-stomp-back-to-the-rook |accessdate=31 May 2019|title=Tropidelic Stomp Back to the Rook|date=March 27, 2019}}</ref>. Since 2017, Tropidelic has also hosted their own annual grassroots music festival,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wksu.org/post/shuffle-funkhip-hop-group-tropidelic-rides-momentum-festival-album-2018#stream/0 |accessdate=18 February 2019|title=Shuffle: Funk/Hip-Hop Group Tropidelic Rides Momentum of Festival, Album into 2018}}</ref> [http://www.thefreakstomp.com The Freakstomp Music Festival].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.cleveland.com/music/index.ssf/2018/08/incuya_music_festival_kent-bor.html | title=InCuya Music Festival: Kent-born Tropidelic takes the stage on Sunday| date=2018-08-20}}</ref>\n\n== The Freakstomp Music Festival ==\nTropidelic started hosting a music festival in 2017. [http://thefreakstomp.com The Freakstomp Music Festival] is named after their song \"Freakstomp\" off of their 2015 album ''Police State'' and is hosted in annually in August. After hosting the first two events in Medina, OH, the event has most recently moved to Clear Fork Adventure Park in Butler, OH. The weekend event hosts national and local acts, including artists such as [[Too Many Zooz]], Bumpin Uglies, Mike Pinto, and [[Afroman]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Freakstomp Music Festival |url=https://www.thefreakstomp.com/ |website=The Freakstomp |accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=Freakstomp Music Festival |url=https://www.clevescene.com/cleveland/freakstomp-music-festival/Event?oid=29054689}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Details Announced for This Year's Freakstomp Festival |url=https://www.clevescene.com/scene-and-heard/archives/2018/06/19/details-announced-for-this-years-freakstomp-festival}}</ref>\n\n== Discography<ref>{{cite web |title=Tropidelic on Apple Music |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/artist/tropidelic/359319340 |website=Apple Music |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Album !! Year of Release\n|-\n| Here in the Heights || 2019\n|-\n| Heavy is the Head || 2017\n|-\n| The Hard North || 2016\n|-\n| Go Down with the Ship || 2016\n|-\n| Police State || 2015\n|-\n| All Heads Unite || 2012\n|-\n| Erie Tides & Irie Vibes || 2011\n|-\n| Tree City Exodus|| 2008\n|-\n|}\n\n== Lineup<ref>{{cite web|title=Reggae Band Tropidelic Has Set Its Goals High |url=http://loyolaphoenix.com/2017/04/reggae-band-tropidelic-set-goals-high/ |website=[[Loyola Phoenix]]|accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> ==\n* Matthew Roads: Guitar/Vocals\n* James Begin: Trombone/Vocals\n* Bobby Chronic: Guitar\n* David Pags: Bass\n* Derek McBryde: Trumpet\n* Rex Larkman: Drums\n* Frank Toncar: Sax, Percussion and Keys\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official site|http://tropidelic.com/}}\n\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Ohio]]\n[[Category:American reggae musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Kent, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2008]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Tropidelic\n| image           = [[File:2019 Press Photo (Michael Clare @mikecimages).jpg|200px]]\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| landscape       = yes\n| alt             = \n| caption         = ''The members of Tropidelic''\n| background      = group_or_band\n| alias           = \n| origin          = [[Cleveland, Ohio]]\n| genre           = [[Funk music|Funk]], [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Hip Hop music|Hip Hop]], [[Reggae music|Reggae]]\n| years_active    = 2008 - Present\n| label           = \n| associated_acts = \n| website         = http://www.tropidelic.com\n| current_members = Bobby Chronic, Derek McBryde, James Begin, Matthew Roads, Pags, Rex Larkman\n| past_members    = \n| module          = \n| module2         = \n| module3         = \n}}\n\n{{short description|American band}}\n<!--[[File:Live Action.jpeg|thumb|Tropidelic performing live in Cleveland, Ohio]]-->\n'''Tropidelic''' is an American band from [[Cleveland]], Ohio. Tropidelic infuses multiple genres into a style that's a blend of [[reggae rock]], [[hip-hop]] and high energy [[funk]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.axs.com/interview-tropidelic-frontman-matt-roads-talks-heavy-is-the-head-follo-132482 |website=[[AXS (company)]]|last=Cohen|first=Sari|date=10 August 2018|accessdate=31 May 2019|title=Interview: Tropidelic frontman Matt Roads talks \u2018Heavy Is The Head\u2019 follow-up and the upcoming InCuya Music Festival}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nTropidelic was formed by founding member Matthew Roads at [[Kent State University]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tribtoday.com/life/ticket/2019/05/tropidelic-heads-trop-the-block/ |website=[[Tribune Chronicle]]|last=Gatta|first=John Patrick|date=16 May 2019|accessdate=31 May 2019|title=Tropidelic heads Trop the Block}}</ref>, located in [[Kent, Ohio]], in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.clevescene.com/cleveland/meet-the-band-tropidelic/Content?oid=4815966 | title=Meet the Band: Tropidelic|website=[[Cleveland Scene]]|last=Niesel|first=Jeff|date=30 March 2016|accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref> They self-distributed over 10,000 free copies of their first self-produced EP, Rebirth of the Dope.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.clevescene.com/scene-and-heard/archives/2017/10/16/the-local-reggae-hip-hop-funk-act-tropidelic-makes-forthcoming-album-available-for-preorder |website=The Cleveland Scene |accessdate=18 February 2019|title=The Cleveland Reggae/Hip-Hop/Funk Act Tropidelic Makes Forthcoming Album Available for Preorder }}</ref> The band's second release, and first studio recording, was Tree City Exodus,<ref>{{cite web |title=Tropidelic to let audience preview new CD at the Robin Hood this Friday |author=Kristen Kotz |date=May 1, 2008 |url=http://www.kentwired.com/latest_updates/article_217a68a4-f4b5-5c6f-8f8c-9e0794b89109.html |website=Kent Wired |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> followed by Erie Tides & Irie Vibes. Over the years, the band has evolved through several member changes and the addition of a horn section, leading up to their first full-length album, All Heads Unite, being released in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.heraldpalladium.com/features/five-questions-tropidelic-brings-more-than-the-funk/article_494ef160-5d62-5a41-9a09-bf0cb7acbfc8.html | title=FIVE QUESTIONS: Tropidelic brings more than the funk}}</ref>\n\nSince the release of All Heads Unite, Tropidelic has released five additional albums.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tropidelic on Apple Music |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/artist/tropidelic/359319340 |publisher=iTunes Store |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> Their 2017 album, ''Heavy is the Head'', was released on Pepper's LAW Records<ref>{{cite web |title=First Watch: Tropidelic \u2013 Leviathan |url=https://rootfire.net/first-watch-tropidelic-leviathan/ |website=Rootfire |accessdate=18 February 2019|date=2017-10-26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/heavy-is-the-head/1264001615 |title=Heavy is the Head by Tropidelic |website=Apple Music |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> and reached #3 on the [[Billboard charts]] on December 2, 2017.<ref> {{Cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/music/tropidelic | title=Tropidelic}}</ref> Tropidelic's latest album, Here in the Heights was released on June 7, 2019 through [https://www.ineffablemusic.com/ Ineffable Music Group]. This full-length album features other notable artists such as Angelo Moore of [[Fishbone]], Howi Spangler of [[Ballyhoo!]], and [[Zach Deputy]], among others.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Niesel |first1=Jeff |title=Local Rockers Tropidelic to Release Their New Album on June 7 |url=https://www.clevescene.com/scene-and-heard/archives/2019/05/31/local-rockers-tropidelic-to-release-their-new-album-on-june-7 |website=Cleveland SCENE |accessdate=31 May  2019}}</ref> Here in the Heights peaked at #2 on the Billboard reggae charts on June 22, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tropidelic |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/tropidelic |website=Billboard |accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nTropidelic has been featured at [[Electric Forest Festival]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Past Lineup |url=https://electricforestfestival.com/history/past-lineups/ |website=Electric Forest |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> [[California Roots Music and Arts Festival|California Roots Music & Art Festival]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://californiarootsfestival.com/past-lineups |website=California Roots Music & Art Festival 2018 | title=Past Line-Ups |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> and [[Warped Tour]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eriereader.com/article/tropidelic-stomp-back-to-the-rook |accessdate=31 May 2019|title=Tropidelic Stomp Back to the Rook|date=March 27, 2019}}</ref>. Since 2017, Tropidelic has also hosted their own annual grassroots music festival,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wksu.org/post/shuffle-funkhip-hop-group-tropidelic-rides-momentum-festival-album-2018#stream/0 |accessdate=18 February 2019|title=Shuffle: Funk/Hip-Hop Group Tropidelic Rides Momentum of Festival, Album into 2018}}</ref> [http://www.thefreakstomp.com The Freakstomp Music Festival].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.cleveland.com/music/index.ssf/2018/08/incuya_music_festival_kent-bor.html | title=InCuya Music Festival: Kent-born Tropidelic takes the stage on Sunday| date=2018-08-20}}</ref>\n\n== The Freakstomp Music Festival ==\nTropidelic started hosting a music festival in 2017. [http://thefreakstomp.com The Freakstomp Music Festival] is named after their song \"Freakstomp\" off of their 2015 album ''Police State'' and is hosted in annually in August. After hosting the first two events in Medina, OH, the event has most recently moved to Clear Fork Adventure Park in Butler, OH. The weekend event hosts national and local acts, including artists such as [[Too Many Zooz]], Bumpin Uglies, Mike Pinto, and [[Afroman]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Freakstomp Music Festival |url=https://www.thefreakstomp.com/ |website=The Freakstomp |accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=Freakstomp Music Festival |url=https://www.clevescene.com/cleveland/freakstomp-music-festival/Event?oid=29054689}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Details Announced for This Year's Freakstomp Festival |url=https://www.clevescene.com/scene-and-heard/archives/2018/06/19/details-announced-for-this-years-freakstomp-festival}}</ref>\n\n== Discography<ref>{{cite web |title=Tropidelic on Apple Music |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/artist/tropidelic/359319340 |website=Apple Music |accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Album !! Year of Release\n|-\n| Here in the Heights || 2019\n|-\n| Heavy is the Head || 2017\n|-\n| The Hard North || 2016\n|-\n| Go Down with the Ship || 2016\n|-\n| Police State || 2015\n|-\n| All Heads Unite || 2012\n|-\n| Erie Tides & Irie Vibes || 2011\n|-\n| Tree City Exodus|| 2008\n|-\n|}\n\n== Lineup<ref>{{cite web|title=Reggae Band Tropidelic Has Set Its Goals High |url=http://loyolaphoenix.com/2017/04/reggae-band-tropidelic-set-goals-high/ |website=[[Loyola Phoenix]]|accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> ==\n* Matthew Roads: Guitar/Vocals\n* James Begin: Trombone/Vocals\n* Bobby Chronic: Guitar\n* David Pags: Bass\n* Derek McBryde: Trumpet\n* Rex Larkman: Drums\n* Frank Toncar: Sax, Percussion and Keys\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official site|http://tropidelic.com/}}\n\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Ohio]]\n[[Category:American reggae musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Kent, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2008]]\n", "name_user": "Chevontez", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground:corrected founding member information. Matthew's last name was incorrect and lacked cofounding name.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tropidelic"}
